e nineteenth century to those applying similar ideas to tomorrow’s technology two hundred years later. Lopez takes in many a utopian visionary in her tour of dreamers of disconnection, from theorists and architects to industrialists and engineers. Technology and design are the centrepieces for these projects, and their complexity, particularly around sustainable supplies of energy, food and water, so often find solutions in aesthetics.Whether these models were based around single homes or whole cities, Dreams of disconnection reveals that there is much to be learnt and marvelled at in the history of self-sufficient design.This book is relevant to both United Nations Sustainable Development Goals 7 and 11, Affordable and clean energy and Sustainable cities and communities  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPublic utilities. 0aSustainable living. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Geography.2bisacsh  aAffordable and clean energy.  aAlexander Pike.  aSustainable cities and communities.  aautonomous house.  aautonomy.  aenvironmental design.  ahistory of architecture.  ahistory of environment.  ahistory of technology.  ainfrastructural studies.  amicro-grids.  aself-sufficiency.1 aLopez, Fanny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614690840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526146908423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526146908/original  a978-3-11-128198-8  Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles